\indent Figure 1 shows the output and transfer characteristics of the device at different wavelengths before and after plasma treatment. Comparing Fig. 1a)
and 1c), it can be seen that the drain-source current increases two-fold for illuminated samples after 2 seconds of plasma exposure at the highest incident power. Figs. 1b) and 1d) show the transfer curves for the same sample, before and after plasma treatment. Thethreshold voltage of the untreated device is shifted drastically to the negative gate biases once higher power illumination occurs. The associated inability to turn off the carrier-rich FET channel at standard gate biases is evident from the plots, where the output current stays firmly above 10$^{-7}$ A even at V$_{GS}$ =  - 60 V. After plasma treatment, the level of output current in the threshold region drops by close to 1 order of magnitude and the threshold is seen to shift to more positive gate biases indicating hole doping in the material (ref). In addition, at low laser powers it can be seen that the MoS$_2$ now possesses a weak ambipolar response past the gate threshold, indicating hole conduction caused by the likely presence of plasma-created oxides. However, the output current in the saturation region of the gate curve has now improved by one order of magnitude under all illumination powers. The dark gated current is decreased slightly, indicating the necessity of illumination for performance improvement after plasma treatment.\\
\indent Figs. 2a) and 2c), track the extracted MoS$_2$ field effect mobility ($\mu_{fe}$) before and after chemical reaction with the plasma at 488 nm and 632 nm respectively. Even with no laser illumination, the mobility is seen to improve in the plasma-treated samples by just under 1 order of magnitude. When the device is exposed to plasma, the mobility of the carriers increases 10-fold with rising laser power. Similarly, in Figs. 2b) and 2d), the output current for the respective wavelength illuminations is seen to improve slightly once plasma treatment takes place. The photoresponsivity and mobility enhancements are summarised for the two wavelengths in Table 1.\\
